      <h2 id="supply-chain-volatility"><i class="fas fa-shield-halved mr-3 text-[#489DF9]"></i>Navigating Supply Chain Volatility and Unit Rate Management</h2>
      <p>
        In 2025, material prices can change in the time it takes to submit a bid and receive an approval. Static <strong>Unit Rates</strong> are no longer sufficient. Custom software allows for real-time price feeds and dynamic adjustments based on local supplier quotes. This agility is critical for maintaining margins in an era of rapid inflation and logistical disruptions.
      </p>
      <p>
        Furthermore, digital systems facilitate better <strong>Bid Leveling</strong>. When comparing quotes from multiple suppliers, the ability to quickly import data and normalize it against your estimate ensures you are making the most cost-effective procurement decisions.
      </p>

      <h2 id="feedback-loop"><i class="fas fa-rotate-right mr-3 text-[#489DF9]"></i>Closing the Feedback Loop: Job Costing and Post-Project Analysis</h2>
      <p>
        The estimating process does not end when the contract is signed. To truly optimize <strong>material estimation for construction</strong>, builders must implement a robust feedback loop. <strong>Job Costing</strong> data from completed projects should flow back into the estimating system to refine future unit rates and waste factors.
      </p>
      <p>
        If your actual concrete waste on the last three projects was 12% but your estimates are still using 5%, you are losing money on every bid. Custom software centralizes this data, allowing for post-mortem analysis that turns past mistakes into future profits.
      </p>

